Do I need an HDMI cable for the Google TV Streamer (4K)?

Yes, an HDMI 2.1 cable is required for use of the Google TV Streamer (4K). The Google TV Streamer (4K) does not come with a HDMI 2.1 cable, but that can be purchased separately.

How do I set up my Google TV Streamer (4K)?

You can set up your Google TV Streamer (4K) by following the steps outlined on your TV when you first plug in your device. For more information, visit this Help Centre page that contains useful setup directions and ways to best use the Google TV Streamer (4K).

What can I use the Google TV Streamer Voice Remote's customizable button for?

The Google TV Streamer Voice Remote comes with a new customizable button, which you can program to immediately launch your favorite app, switch inputs, or open the home panel to control your smart home. Visit this Help Centre page to learn more.

How can I control my smart home devices using my Google TV Streamer (4K)?

The Google TV Streamer (4K) has a home panel where you can control all your favorite smart home devices. It can be accessed by long pressing the home button on the Voice Remote, or through the customizable button. Learn more about the home panel on this Help Centre page.

What resolution does the Google TV Streamer (4K) support?

The Google TV Streamer (4K) supports up to 4K HDR with Dolby Vision.

How do I set up parental controls on my Google TV Streamer (4K)?

Google TV supports kids profiles, where parents can set controls to filter age-appropriate entertainment, limit watch time, and set a bedtime. Learn more on how to set up the controls on this Help Center page.

How do I use the Find My Remote function?

You can locate your remote by pressing the button on the back of your Google TV Streamer (4K), or using your voice by saying "Hey Google, find my remote".

How can I use my phone to cast to a Google TV Streamer (4K)-enabled TV?

You can cast content on your phone to the Google TV Streamer (4K)-enabled TV by following these steps:
Connect your phone to the same Wi-Fi network as your Google TV. Open the app that has the content you want to cast. In the app, find and select Cast. On your phone, select the name of your TV. When Cast changes color, you're successfully connected.
To stop casting, on your phone, select Cast and then Disconnect.

How do I manage my accounts or profiles on the Google TV Streamer (4K)?

You can set up multiple accounts so each member of the household has their own Google TV profile. Downloaded apps and app login details can be used across profiles, so there is no need to start from scratch each time you set up a new profile. Learn more about setting up and managing user profiles on this Help Center page.

How is Dolby Atmos different from Atmos passthrough?

Dolby Atmos on the Google TV Streamer delivers immersive, three dimensional sound without the need for a sound decoding system such as an AV receiver. For devices that don't support true Dolby Atmos (like Chromecast with Google TV) but offer passthrough capability, another Dolby Atmos capable sound system would be required to deliver the same effect.
